 signalling pathway","Disrupts microtubule formation and cell replication","Inhibits calcineurin phosphatase","Blocks purine synthesis and DNA replication"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGuanine analogues such as azathioprine work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking purine synthesis and \u003C/strong\u003Eincorporating their metabolites into DNA to block\u003Cstrong\u003E DNA replication\u003C/strong\u003E. This particularly affects rapidly dividing cells like T and B lymphocytes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents interleukin-2 receptor binding\u003C/strong\u003E: this mechanism belongs to monoclonal antibodies such as basiliximab, which target the interleukin-2 receptor on T cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits mTOR signalling pathway\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of action of sirolimus and everolimus, which block growth factor-mediated lymphocyte proliferation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisrupts microtubule formation and cell replication\u003C/strong\u003E: this mechanism belongs to medications like colchicine, which interferes with cell division by preventing microtubule assembly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits calcineurin phosphatase\u003C/strong\u003E describes how ciclosporin and tacrolimus work, preventing T cell activation by blocking calcineurin-mediated signalling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy preventing lymphocyte proliferation, guanine analogues reduce the immune response against transplanted organs and suppress autoimmune reactions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Guanine analogues like azathioprine are converted to metabolites which inhibit purine synthesis and incorporate 